3Cp\u003EChief cells are the main functional cells of the parathyroid glands responsible for producing parathyroid hormone. They have distinct microscopic features:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E8 microns in diameter\u003C/strong\u003E is the typical size of chief cells, making them smaller than oxyphil cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ENot \u003Cstrong\u003E12 microns in diameter\u003C/strong\u003E - this is closer to the size of oxyphil cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThey have eccentrically placed nuclei, not \u003Cstrong\u003Ecentrally placed nuclei\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThey contain numerous \u003Cstrong\u003Esecretory granules\u003C/strong\u003E in their cytoplasm\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThey have basophilic cytoplasm, not \u003Cstrong\u003Eacidophilic cytoplasm\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese characteristics help distinguish chief cells from other cell types in the parathyroid glands.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chief cells are small basophilic cells in the parathyroid gland that secrete parathyroid hormone","Chief cells contain numerous secretory granules and have eccentrically placed nuclei","Chief cells measure approximately 8 microns in diameter"],"references":["Goldenring JR, Nam KT, Mills JC. The origin of pre-neoplastic metaplasia in the stomach: chief cells emerge from the Mist. Exp Cell Res. 2011 Nov 15;317(19):2759-64. doi: 10.1016/j.yexcr.2011.08.017. Epub 2011 Aug 31. PMID: 21907708; PMCID: PMC3210373.","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevie